<br>
Try to always make stuff in the mid-low orange range of difficulty.  For weapon crafting that is about 7-10pts higher than your current skill level.<br>
<br>
Accept that you are going to spend a certain amount of time making trinkets.  The power-level path does not raise all subskills evenly.  The leather trinkets are generally more expensive than the wood trinkets.  Fortunately, some new trinkets have been added, so you no longer have to spend a period of time making trinkets that con red to you... that was very expensive.<br>
<br>
The weapons that use the least amount of metal are usually thrust weapons; try to skill up by making thrust weapons.<br>
<br>
I found that the least expensive skill path was to make these items, in this order: dagger, stiletto, main gauche, rapier, gladius, round shield.  That series will get you through 100 skill points for each material level.  Round shields are very inexpensive to make... so start making round shields as soon as you can (when they are 15 points higher than your current skill level) and for as long as you can -- until they turn blue.  All other items you should make only while they are orange; as soon as they con yellow to make, move on to the next higher item.  (In practice, you will find there's a few spots where you will need to make a few yellow items before you can move on to the next higher item.)<br>
<br>
The first items are all swords, and will develop metalworking and leatherworking subskills, but not woodworking.  When you are ready to start making the round shields, you'll need to make wood trinkets to raise your woodworking skill before you can make the round shields.  At the end of the woodworking menu are things like breadboards, curio boxes, jewelry boxes, etc. that have no purpose except as something you can make to raise skill -- called trinkets.  Pick one that is orange, and start grinding... a couple of hundred breadboards later your woodworking skill will be high enough to start making round shields.<br>
<br>
